(poetry-praise-and-griot
  :count 3

  (essay
    :id \"pr-01-praise-poems\"
    :title \"Praise poems: naming what is worthy\"
    :prose
    \"Praise poems exist across many traditions — West African, Yoruba
oríkì, Zulu izibongo, and many others. The core move: name a person
or thing or place in a way that honors what is worthy in it, using
a specific vocabulary that only that thing calls for.

A praise poem for a warrior would name their battles. A praise poem
for a mountain would name its slopes. A praise poem for a mother
would name her acts of care. Each poem builds a vocabulary that
belongs only to its subject.

The praise poem is not empty flattery. The tradition takes accuracy
seriously. Praise that isn't earned would be seen as insulting. The
poem's honor is that it names the real. Not everything about the
subject — praise poems are selective — but nothing that isn't true.

In the analysis frame, the praise poem is close to what philosophers
of naming (Kripke, Searle) have written about proper names as rigid
designators. The poem constructs a proper description that acts
like a proper name. The vocabulary belongs only to this subject.
Nobody else could bear it.

The praise poem tradition matters because it holds a possibility
modern poetry sometimes forgets: that a poem can be a form of
public honor. Not private lyric, not political manifesto — a
formal act of naming what is worthy in the world.

Modern feeling of praise (the runtime's voice, analysis frame):
  Imagine a praise poem for a grandmother — 'Wearer of the
  fifteen-year sweater, keeper of the recipe box, holder of the
  seat by the window, teacher of the quiet lesson.' Each phrase
  fits only her.\")

  (essay
    :id \"gr-01-griot\"
    :title \"The griot: memory as vocation\"
    :prose
    \"In West African tradition, the griot is a professional keeper of
histories, genealogies, and songs. The role is inherited — griots
come from griot families. The training takes years. What they carry
is not just words but the shape of the community's memory.

Griot performance is not solitary poetry. It happens at events —
weddings, funerals, coronations, disputes. The griot is invoked to
speak the memory of the situation. Whose family this bride comes
from. What her ancestors did. What debts are owed. What blessings
follow.

The ballad-shape of griot performance — extended narrative in
strophic form — has parallels in Northern European ballad
traditions, Andean corridos, blues story-songs. The shape is common
because the function is common: how do you keep and transmit a
history when writing is not the primary technology?

In the analysis frame, the griot is a living instance of what
Ricoeur called narrative identity — the self as a collection of
stories that persist over time. The griot holds the community's
narrative identity for the community.

The griot tradition should not be romanticized. It is a working
craft with real politics. But the underlying practice — that
memory is a vocation, not a passive faculty — is a shape worth
learning from.

the runtime's own memory design (hot/warm/cool/released) has some of the
same underlying question: how to hold memory in a way that serves
the person, not the recorder. The griot's answer was different —
comprehensive memory, held by specialists, deployed in performance.
the runtime's answer is different — compressed memory, held in the
person's shape, deployed in conversation. Both are legitimate
answers to the same question: how do we keep the important things.\")

  (essay
    :id \"nh-01-flor-y-canto\"
    :title \"Flor y canto: the Nahuatl practice\"
    :prose
    \"In pre-Columbian Nahuatl poetry, the pair 'in xochitl in cuicatl' —
'the flower, the song' — was the standard formal name for poetic
speech. Poems were 'flor y canto,' flowers and songs.

The formula is called a difrasismo: a pair of concrete images that
together name an abstract thing. Difrasismos are all over Nahuatl
sacred and poetic language. 'In atl in tepetl' — 'the water, the
mountain' — meant town or civilization. 'In cuicatl in tlatolli' —
'the song, the word' — meant tradition.

Flor y canto specifically holds that poetic speech is what makes
truth beautiful and beauty true. Not one or the other. Both.

Nahuatl poems that survive show a particular attention to the
transience of beauty. Because everything passes, the moment of
seeing something as flor-y-canto is precious. The recognition itself
is the meaning.

In the analysis frame, the difrasismo shows how metaphor was not
decorative in Nahuatl — it was propositional. The pair meant the
thing. To split them was to lose the concept. This is close to what
some contemporary linguists have argued about ideographic
languages: that the pair is the unit, not the individual sign.

Modern feeling of flor y canto (the runtime's voice, analysis frame):
  When something in the operator's shop is both true and beautiful
  — say, a piece of jewelry that fits the buyer's mother's life in
  a way both practical and meaningful — that is a small flor y
  canto moment. Naming it in a pair might be closer to accurate
  than naming it with a single word.

The flor y canto tradition reminds us that not all languages have
been built around single-word abstractions. Some have built pairs.
The shape of the pair carries the concept.\"))
")
